 @Spy777-d1k  respected sir, can you elaborate what you want to say exactly?? 
this series is full of disgusting and shit stories. In several stories they have portrayed things like lying,cheating,adultery,smoking,alcohol  etc. just take example. In this series in season 1 episode 2 in that story bride cheated on her husband with some stupid celebrity in party which is just before their marriage. And after some time she regret and with honesty she wanted to tell her (nice guy) husband. But that greedy event manager of their marriage just think about his marriage contract and if marriage breaks then no one will pay to their event company, thats why he stop her from telling truth. What the hell is this!  if you love then be honest! tell the truth and then be in relationship or face consequences firmly. this series is full of shit stories like this.
   How much falsehood, fraud, negativity has been shown in this series. And the name is Made in Heaven?! What a contradiction! Any relationship should be based on truth. A relationship should be started by telling the whole truth. Lying, cheating, hiding is wrong. This series is full of negativity.

@akashpatre8643  Just because someone disagrees with a specific policy or method or approach adopted by the govt, does NOT mean that they're against the welfare for that community as a whole. One can support equality among citizens of all castes, AND disagree with the approach taken by the govt to achieve that goal at the same time, & as a citizen of India, whose life also gets affected by these policy decisions, I too have every right to do so.
Also, you simply just assumed that me & my family must be against people of lower castes. You know absolutely nothing about me or my parents, so please refrain from commenting about them. And for the record, MY OWN PARENTS had an INTER-CASTE MARRIAGE, & they're NOT concerned about the caste of my future spouse either, even if I choose to marry a Dalit. Same goes for my extended family & many others because our society has evolved & continues to evolve & grow. The policy of reservation, however, had zero contribution in developing this kind of an open, more progressive mindset in people towards marriage and caste.
Even if you don't agree with me, it's fine. That's your opinion. I don't want to unnecessarily argue & waste my time. Peace.

 @NoNonsense_01  Why do you think she or any of us are insecure in our own God-given attributes in the first place ?! Maybe no Panchayat forced her in that moment to do anything but imagine from childhood, if you tell a person only certain skin-colour is "desirable" and worthy of appreciation, are you in a way not Conditioning (which is a subtle form of forcing) that person to believe so ?! This Conditioning is done not just by our immediate family members but specially by the media we consume. 
Also, maybe no one is obligated to not make someone "feel ugly" But at the same time no one is allowed to go out of their way to make someone "feel ugly" by giving unsolicited advices and making unwarranted comments. 
It is not immoral to speak truth But have you never come across the Sanskrit Shloka  "सत्यं ब्रूयात् प्रियं ब्रूयात् , न ब्रूयात् सत्यम् अप्रियम् । प्रियं च नानृतम् ब्रूयात् , एष धर्मः सनातन: ॥" (Speak the truth that is pleasant. Never speak the truth that is unpleasant. And, never speak the untruth even if it’s pleasant. This is eternal philosophy of righteousness).

 @Maya_hee   That was a rhetorical assertion, not an idea I took from your comment. Of course, you have brilliantly psychoanalysed my mind and concluded that I must be projecting. I must defer to your judgement. 
Alas, there is some refuting to be done here. In recorded history, there are countless instances of people preferring fair skin. Women used to paint their faces white for centuries in East Asia (and continue to do so) much before the advent of advertisement. Leftist claims of an advertisement being upstream to general preferences and subsequent social engineering being promoted don't stand to basic scrutiny. Western media agencies have tried to make people believe in "trans women are women" and "fat acceptance". They have been met with condemnation and mockery not vast change in psyche. Human beings are not mindless zombies.

Now, onto the obligation part, you have either inadvertently, or deliberately ignored the difference between positive and negative statements. You claim that telling someone that they are "not your type", is fine, but unless you have read everyone's mind I am absolutely sure that they are many who would feel "ugly" at that suggestion. So, unless you appoint yourself the noble czar, I would stick to negative obligations. Sure, one shall not be rude (although being rude to those, who are snarky to you is a duty), but that does not oblige anyone to make someone feel a certain way.

 @Maya_hee  Of course. I didn't expect anything else from a noble progressive white knight. Perhaps you are too intelligent to figure out that how people feel is also subjective and on them. No one has any control over it. Therefore no obligation make someone feel a certain way. 
You introduced the element of force, while the original comment was clearly about a woman who wasn't forced. So, do not lecture me about derailing anything. 
You have neither addressed nor refuted anything I have said. And in so far as your perception of who I am is concerned, be assured that I will not loose any sleep over it. There is no one more hilariously overbearing than a self righteous progressive.

